A briefing has been given to the parliament about the fire that engulfed the National Assembly. eNCA's Lindsay Dentinger is following that story for us. Courtesy of #DStv403  CAPE TOWN - There are still no clear answers as to how Parliament's security was breached on 2 January, leading to its main building being razed. This as opposition parties seek to lay the blame at the door of Public Works Minister, Patricia de Lille. READ: Parliament fire | DA accuses De Lille of 'cover-up' The Public Works Department says it can’t reveal information about CCTV footage or the damages sustained because the buildings are now a crime scene. But Parliament has confirmed none of its security protection officers was on duty that day.